	<div class="commentBody">	
		<div id="comment_body_4595888">John,

<p>Appreciate you taking the time to address this matter publicly as many of us were wondering what was going on. I've been one of the 'lucky' few to have downloaded this leaked alpha before the fan-sites and media started reporting on it.

</p><p>From what I can tell id has come a long way, if set up properly the alpha looks spectacular, and very playable. I can see this has implications for the company that caused the leak but from an end-user and analyst perspective I can tell you it is all good.

</p><p>What I think is a far greater problem is the fact that many of the fan-sites kept quiet about it as they feared loss of advertisement opportunities or repercussions from the developer in question. I don't have to tell you that this severely undermines their journalistic integrity and freedom of speech.

</p><p>I'm guessing id software tried to limit the damage by calling in some favors with these websites and the moderators of their forums, but really isn't that simply adding to the problem? Making something hard to come by and secretive will only increase the demand.

</p><p>I'd say a short blurb on the id website and news posting on these websites explaining what happened and stressing the fact that this is an alpha version that's nowhere near the final release in terms of features, graphics or performance would certainly put matters back into perspective.

</p><p>De duobus malis, minus est semper eligendum

